<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="147" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="6.[189,303,989,1015]" box="[189,303,989,1015]" pageId="6" pageNumber="147">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,303,989,1015]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="6" pageNumber="147" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,303,989,1015]" pageId="6" pageNumber="147">Remarks</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[187,1400,1038,1779]" pageId="6" pageNumber="147">
According to the molecular data, partially supported by the shape of the paramere (
<bibRefCitation author="Salnitska M. &amp; Solodovnikov A." pageId="6" pageNumber="147" pagination="1 - 16" refId="ref9137" refString="Salnitska M. &amp; Solodovnikov A. 2021. DNA barcode sheds light on species boundaries in the common morphologically variable rove beetle Quedius umbrinus - complex that puzzled taxonomists for more than a century (Coleoptera, Staphylinidae). Systematics and Biodiversity 0 (0): 1 - 16. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 14772000.2021.1943559" type="book chapter" year="2021">Salnitska &amp; Solodovnikov 2021</bibRefCitation>
), the former single species 
<taxonomicName authority="Erichson, 1839" authorityName="Erichson" authorityYear="1839" box="[786,1140,1075,1102]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Quedius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="147" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="umbrinus">
<emphasis box="[786,941,1075,1102]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="147">Q. umbrinus</emphasis>
Erichson, 1839
</taxonomicName>
(for example, sensu 
<bibRefCitation author="Salnitska M. &amp; Solodovnikov A." box="[189,585,1113,1139]" pageId="6" pageNumber="147" pagination="117 - 159" refId="ref8995" refString="Salnitska M. &amp; Solodovnikov A. 2018 a. Revision of the Quedius fauna of Middle Asia (Coleoptera, Staphylinidae, Staphylininae). Deutsche Entomologische Zeitschrift 65 (2): 117 - 159." type="journal article" year="2018">Salnitska &amp; Solodovnikov 2018a</bibRefCitation>
) is divided into three species, 
<taxonomicName authority="Salnitska &amp; Solodovnikov, 2021" authorityName="Salnitska &amp; Solodovnikov" authorityYear="2021" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Quedius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="147" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="volkeri">
<emphasis box="[951,1071,1113,1139]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="147">Q. volkeri</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Salnitska M. &amp; Solodovnikov A." pageId="6" pageNumber="147" pagination="1 - 16" refId="ref9137" refString="Salnitska M. &amp; Solodovnikov A. 2021. DNA barcode sheds light on species boundaries in the common morphologically variable rove beetle Quedius umbrinus - complex that puzzled taxonomists for more than a century (Coleoptera, Staphylinidae). Systematics and Biodiversity 0 (0): 1 - 16. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 14772000.2021.1943559" type="book chapter" year="2021">Salnitska &amp; Solodovnikov, 2021</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Erichson" authorityYear="1839" box="[261,406,1151,1177]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Quedius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="147" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="umbrinus">
<emphasis box="[261,406,1151,1177]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="147">Q. umbrinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<emphasis box="[459,695,1151,1177]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="147">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lohse" authorityYear="1958" box="[459,691,1151,1177]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Quedius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="147" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pseudoumbrinus">Q. pseudoumbrinus</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
The first species is a local endemic of the Western Caucasus, while 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Erichson" authorityYear="1839" box="[267,422,1188,1215]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Quedius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="147" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="umbrinus">
<emphasis box="[267,422,1188,1215]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="147">Q. umbrinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lohse" authorityYear="1958" box="[488,728,1188,1215]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Quedius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="147" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pseudoumbrinus">
<emphasis box="[488,728,1188,1215]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="147">Q. pseudoumbrinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are widespread West Palaearctic species with largely overlapping distributions. Unfortunately, neither the material of the former ‘ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Erichson" authorityYear="1839" box="[1086,1234,1226,1252]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Quedius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="147" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="umbrinus">
<emphasis box="[1086,1234,1226,1252]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="147">Q. umbrinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
’ from Middle Asia reported in 
<bibRefCitation author="Salnitska M. &amp; Solodovnikov A." box="[381,785,1264,1290]" pageId="6" pageNumber="147" pagination="117 - 159" refId="ref8995" refString="Salnitska M. &amp; Solodovnikov A. 2018 a. Revision of the Quedius fauna of Middle Asia (Coleoptera, Staphylinidae, Staphylininae). Deutsche Entomologische Zeitschrift 65 (2): 117 - 159." type="journal article" year="2018">Salnitska &amp; Solodovnikov (2018a)</bibRefCitation>
, nor the material from this region used in 
<bibRefCitation author="Salnitska M. &amp; Solodovnikov A." pageId="6" pageNumber="147" pagination="1 - 16" refId="ref9137" refString="Salnitska M. &amp; Solodovnikov A. 2021. DNA barcode sheds light on species boundaries in the common morphologically variable rove beetle Quedius umbrinus - complex that puzzled taxonomists for more than a century (Coleoptera, Staphylinidae). Systematics and Biodiversity 0 (0): 1 - 16. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 14772000.2021.1943559" type="book chapter" year="2021">Salnitska &amp; Solodovnikov (2021)</bibRefCitation>
are of DNA-grade. Among the material from Middle Asia studied in 
<bibRefCitation author="Salnitska M. &amp; Solodovnikov A." pageId="6" pageNumber="147" pagination="1 - 16" refId="ref9137" refString="Salnitska M. &amp; Solodovnikov A. 2021. DNA barcode sheds light on species boundaries in the common morphologically variable rove beetle Quedius umbrinus - complex that puzzled taxonomists for more than a century (Coleoptera, Staphylinidae). Systematics and Biodiversity 0 (0): 1 - 16. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 14772000.2021.1943559" type="book chapter" year="2021">Salnitska &amp; Solodovnikov (2021)</bibRefCitation>
, only the male specimens from Chilik River of Kungey Alatau in 
<collectingCountry box="[1214,1351,1339,1365]" name="Kazakhstan" pageId="6" pageNumber="147">Kazakhstan</collectingCountry>
can be identified as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lohse" authorityYear="1958" box="[376,606,1377,1403]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Quedius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="147" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pseudoumbrinus">
<emphasis box="[376,606,1377,1403]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="147">Q. pseudoumbrinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
based on the more parallel-sided, not apically rhomboid paramere. The shape of the paramere in males from the Dzhungar Mountains in 
<collectingCountry box="[1015,1152,1414,1440]" name="Kazakhstan" pageId="6" pageNumber="147">Kazakhstan</collectingCountry>
and from N of Issyk Kul Lake in 
<collectingCountry box="[332,466,1452,1478]" name="Kyrgyzstan" pageId="6" pageNumber="147">Kyrgyzstan</collectingCountry>
in 
<bibRefCitation author="Salnitska M. &amp; Solodovnikov A." box="[501,890,1452,1478]" pageId="6" pageNumber="147" pagination="1 - 16" refId="ref9137" refString="Salnitska M. &amp; Solodovnikov A. 2021. DNA barcode sheds light on species boundaries in the common morphologically variable rove beetle Quedius umbrinus - complex that puzzled taxonomists for more than a century (Coleoptera, Staphylinidae). Systematics and Biodiversity 0 (0): 1 - 16. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 14772000.2021.1943559" type="book chapter" year="2021">Salnitska &amp; Solodovnikov (2021)</bibRefCitation>
does not allow their confident identification as either 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Erichson" authorityYear="1839" box="[294,441,1490,1516]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Quedius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="147" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="umbrinus">
<emphasis box="[294,441,1490,1516]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="147">Q. umbrinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
or 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lohse" authorityYear="1958" box="[480,709,1490,1516]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Quedius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="147" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pseudoumbrinus">
<emphasis box="[480,709,1490,1516]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="147">Q. pseudoumbrinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Based on the shape of the paramere, the material reported as ‘ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Erichson" authorityYear="1839" box="[231,379,1527,1554]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Quedius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="147" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="umbrinus">
<emphasis box="[231,379,1527,1554]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="147">Q. umbrinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
’ in 
<bibRefCitation author="Salnitska M. &amp; Solodovnikov A." box="[425,835,1527,1553]" pageId="6" pageNumber="147" pagination="117 - 159" refId="ref8995" refString="Salnitska M. &amp; Solodovnikov A. 2018 a. Revision of the Quedius fauna of Middle Asia (Coleoptera, Staphylinidae, Staphylininae). Deutsche Entomologische Zeitschrift 65 (2): 117 - 159." type="journal article" year="2018">Salnitska &amp; Solodovnikov (2018a)</bibRefCitation>
is likely to be 
<taxonomicName authority="(Salnitska &amp; Solodovnikov 2021)" baseAuthorityName="Salnitska &amp; Solodovnikov" baseAuthorityYear="2021" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Quedius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="147" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pseudoumbrinus">
<emphasis box="[1013,1243,1527,1554]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="147">Q. pseudoumbrinus</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Salnitska M. &amp; Solodovnikov A." pageId="6" pageNumber="147" pagination="1 - 16" refId="ref9137" refString="Salnitska M. &amp; Solodovnikov A. 2021. DNA barcode sheds light on species boundaries in the common morphologically variable rove beetle Quedius umbrinus - complex that puzzled taxonomists for more than a century (Coleoptera, Staphylinidae). Systematics and Biodiversity 0 (0): 1 - 16. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 14772000.2021.1943559" type="book chapter" year="2021">Salnitska &amp; Solodovnikov 2021</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, though this needs to be tested with molecular data. It is noteworthy that all material of ‘ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Erichson" authorityYear="1839" box="[229,375,1602,1629]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Quedius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="147" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="umbrinus">
<emphasis box="[229,375,1602,1629]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="147">Q. umbrinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
’ from Middle Asia from both of our abovementioned studies with precise bionomic data was collected at higher elevations in the mountains. Thus, the Middle Asian populations of the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Erichson" authorityYear="1839" box="[1255,1397,1640,1667]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Quedius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="147" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="umbrinus">
<emphasis box="[1255,1397,1640,1667]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="147">Q. umbrinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
complex may be somewhat isolated from the main ranges of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Erichson" authorityYear="1839" box="[916,1064,1678,1704]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Quedius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="147" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="umbrinus">
<emphasis box="[916,1064,1678,1704]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="147">Q. umbrinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Salnitska &amp; Solodovnikov" baseAuthorityYear="2021" box="[1123,1353,1678,1704]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Quedius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="147" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pseudoumbrinus">
<emphasis box="[1123,1353,1678,1704]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="147">Q. pseudoumbrinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. To properly shed light on the identity of ‘ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Erichson" authorityYear="1839" box="[646,794,1715,1742]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Quedius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="147" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="umbrinus">
<emphasis box="[646,794,1715,1742]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="147">Q. umbrinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
’ in Middle Asia in view of the data in 
<bibRefCitation author="Salnitska M. &amp; Solodovnikov A." pageId="6" pageNumber="147" pagination="1 - 16" refId="ref9137" refString="Salnitska M. &amp; Solodovnikov A. 2021. DNA barcode sheds light on species boundaries in the common morphologically variable rove beetle Quedius umbrinus - complex that puzzled taxonomists for more than a century (Coleoptera, Staphylinidae). Systematics and Biodiversity 0 (0): 1 - 16. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 14772000.2021.1943559" type="book chapter" year="2021">Salnitska &amp; Solodovnikov (2021)</bibRefCitation>
, DNA-grade material is needed.
</paragraph>
